With the probable exception of Papar, [MASK] was an uninhabited island until around 870.
The medieval chronicler Ari Thorgilsson said Ingólfr was the first Nordic settler in [MASK], but mentioned that "Papar" – i.e.
Its name means "little island of the papar" (as distinct from Papa Stour), who were Gaelic hermits or Culdees found as far north as [MASK].

The Papar ([ˈpʰaːpar̥]; from Latin papa, via Old Irish, meaning "father" or "pope") were, according to early Icelandic historical sources, a group of Irish or Scottish monks resident in parts of what is now [MASK] at the time of the arrival of the Norsemen on the island.
The Scandinavians began settling in [MASK] in 874 AD, but the oldest source to mention the existence of the Papar was written in the Íslendingabók ("Book of the Icelanders"), between 1122 and 1133.

Several [MASK] toponyms (see Toponymy) have been linked to the Papar, including the island of Papey, as well as the Vestmannaeyjar ("islands of the Westmen") but no archaeological evidence in these places has yet confirmed the link.
